ess license. Net neutrality is the most contested Internet access policy of our time. This book offers an in-depth explanation of the concept, addressing its history since 1999, its engineering, the policy challenges it represents and its legislation and regulation. Various case studies are presented, including Specialized Services and Content Delivery Networks for video over the Internet, and the book goes on to examine the future of net neutrality battles in Europe, the United States and developing countries, as well as offering co-regulatory solutions based on FRAND and non-exclusivity. It will be a must-read for researchers and advocates in the net neutrality debate, as well as those interested in the context of communications regulation, law and economic regulation, human rights discourse and policy, and the impact of science and engineering on policy and governance.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aNetwork neutralityxLaw and legislationzEuropean Union countries. 0aNetwork neutralityxLaw and legislationzGreat Britain. 0aNetwork neutralityxLaw and legislationzUnited States. 7aLAW / Computer & Internet.2bisacsh  aEurope.  aOpen Internet self-regulation.  aQuality of Service.  aUnited States.  acommunications regulators.  acompetition law.  amobile net neutrality.  anet neutrality laws.  anet neutrality regulation.  azero rating practices.1 aMarsden, Christopher T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2017 eBook-Packagez9783111282817oZDB-23-MUP40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526105479zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cove